{
  "texts": [
    "Reliance on platform counterspeech risks backfire effects when ideologically kindred content is tagged as misinformation, entrenching beliefs [67] (Article 27).",
    "This effect might scale if not recognizing longstanding scholarship on selective exposure and homophily, thereby limiting breeding epistemic distrust of institutional fact checkers in polarization contexts [6,144].Psychological Depth and Targeting More broadly, insufficient attention to established emotional, moral intuition and identity-adjacent appeals giving disinformation intrinsic force overlooks extensive models clarifying the depth of human vulnerability beyond narrow information deficits or viral harm frames [41] (Article 26, Code: RA).",
    "In terms of targeting risks, the lack of credible, scalable technical and procedural safeguards against behavioral microtargeting risks enabling manipulative disinformation campaigns (Articles 24, 29-30, Codes: DD, AT, RA).",
    "Since the DSA doesn't outright ban certain ad targeting or recommender practices, determining violations will require case-by-case analysis [78,107].",
    "Lastly, still related to design choices maximizing engagement, addictive design features have raised alarm also for Members of the EU Parliament (MEPs) who voiced their concerns and called for a ban on addictive techniques of recommender systems [55]."
  ]
}